{
  "doc_id": "43557",
  "text": "The seven distinct areas of Tobacyk's paranormal belief scale have been subject to both critique and support by a number of studies. The main critique concerns the number of distinct factors that can be extracted from the available items. Hartmann (1999) and [CITATION_1] argued that only four factors were present, although [CITATION_2] subsequently revised this to five factors, arguing that the subscales of extraordinary life forms and precognition should be removed or revised. In a reply to [CITATION_3] , Tobacyk (1995) agrees that the RPBS provides some theoretically challenging notions to parapsychology (for example, regarding whether belief in extraordinary life forms should be considered as paranormal), but defends the seven factor structure as combining both related and unrelated conceptualisation of a broad area. As such the RPBS has been used extensively in research concerned with areas such as dissociative experiences [CITATION_4] , thinking styles [CITATION_5] , and schizotypy (Hergovich, Schott, & Arendasy, 2008) .",
